Based on the provided documentation, setting up an Amazon Elastic Container Service (ECS) for a production workload involves several key steps, particularly when using the **Blue/Green deployment type** with CodeDeploy. Below is a detailed step-by-step guide, including relevant configurations and code examples extracted from the context.

### Step 1: Create an ECS Cluster
First, you need to create an ECS cluster where your services will run.

```json
{
  "clusterName": "ProductionCluster"
}
```

*Source: [AWS > ECS](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/userguide/create-ecs-cluster.html)*

### Step 2: Define a Load Balancer
Configure either an Application Load Balancer (ALB) or Network Load Balancer (NLB). The load balancer is essential for routing traffic to your tasks.

```json
{
  "loadBalancer": {
    "type": "Application", // or "Network"
    "name": "prod-alb",
    "listeners": [
      {
        "protocol": "HTTP",
        "port": 80,
        "defaultActions": [{ "type": "forward", "targetGroupArn": "arn:aws:elasticloadbalancing:<region>:<account-id>:targetgroup/prod-target-group/1234567890abcdef1" }]
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

*Source: [AWS > ECS > Blue/Green deployment with CodeDeploy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/userguide/blue-green-deployments.html)*

### Step 3: Create an Application and Deployment Group in CodeDeploy
When you initially create a CodeDeploy application and deployment group, define two target groups for the load balancer.

```json
{
  "applicationName": "AppECS-<cluster[:47]>-<service[:47]>", 
  "deploymentGroupName": "DgpECS-<cluster[:47]>-<service[:47]>"
}
```

*Source: [AWS > ECS > Blue/Green deployment with CodeDeploy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/userguide/blue-green-deployment-considerations.html)*

### Step 4: Create an Amazon ECS Service with Blue/Green Deployment
Use the classic Amazon ECS console to create a service that uses the blue/green deployment type. This automatically creates necessary CodeDeploy resources.

```json
{
  "serviceName": "ProductionService",
  "cluster": "ProductionCluster",
  "deploymentType": "BlueGreen",
  "loadBalancers": [
    {
      "name": "prod-alb"
    }
  ],
  "listeners": [
    {
      "protocol": "HTTP",
      "port": 80
    }
  ]
}
```

*Source: [AWS > ECS > Blue/Green deployment with CodeDeploy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/userguide/blue-green-deployment-console.html)*

### Step 5: Configure Traffic Rerouting Settings
Set the traffic rerouting settings to control how production traffic is shifted from the original task set (blue) to the replacement task set (green).

```json
{
  "trafficRoutingConfig": {
    "type": "Immediate", // or "Gradual"
    "gradual": {
      "percentage": 50,
      "intervalInMinutes": 5
    }
  }
}
```

*Source: [AWS > ECS > Blue/Green deployment with CodeDeploy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/userguide/blue-green-traffic-routing.html)*

### Step 6: Define Deployment Configuration
Choose a deployment configuration that specifies how traffic is shifted during the deployment. Options include `CodeDeployDefault.ECSAllAtOnce`, canary, or linear deployments.

```json
{
  "deploymentConfigName": "CodeDeployDefault.ECSAllAtOnce"
}
```

*Source: [AWS > ECS > Blue/Green deployment with CodeDeploy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/userguide/blue-green-deployment-configurations.html)*

### Step 7: Set Up Automatic Rollback (Optional)
Configure automatic rollback settings to ensure that if a deployment fails, traffic is reverted to the original task set.

```json
{
  "rollback": {
    "enabled": true,
    "triggeredBy": ["DEPLOYMENT_FAILURE"]
  }
}
```

*Source: [AWS > ECS > Blue/Green deployment with CodeDeploy](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonECS/latest/userguide/blue-green-rollback.html)*

### Step 8: Monitor and Validate Deployments
After deploying, monitor the deployments via the **Deployments** tab on the Amazon ECS console. Use validation tests during the test traffic phase to ensure the new task set is functioning correctly.

